            <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">President</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>'s
Inaugural Address <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this month</TIMEX> is the <NUMEX TYPE="QUANTITY">53 rd</NUMEX> in the series that began in
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1789</TIMEX>. All are worth a read--not just the highlights, such as <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">George Washington</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Abraham Lincoln</ENAMEX>, and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FDR</ENAMEX>. They will give you a feeling of being there, not as
an omniscient <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">historian</ENAMEX> of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1997</TIMEX> looking back at <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1837 or 1897</TIMEX> but as an ordinary
<ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">citizen</ENAMEX> who shares--and is limited by--the information, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">concerns</ENAMEX>, and the
values of those times. (Thanks to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Columbia University</ENAMEX>, all the addresses can be
